Is Trump yesterday's news?

by GRAYCE MCCORMICK | The National Desk

Fri, November 18th 2022 at 1:36 PM
18
VIEW ALL PHOTOS
Supporters of former President Donald Trump gather outside of Trump Tower Tuesday, Nov. 15, 2022, in New York. (AP Photo/Frank Franklin II)

HUNT VALLEY, Md. (TND) — Former twice-impeached President Donald Trump may not have ability to make headlines in the news like he once did.

Either that, or he may not have news outlets writing good headlines about him like he once did.

He made his “big announcement” from his Mar-a-Lago residence in Florida Tuesday:

“This comeback starts right now. In order to make America great and glorious again, I am tonight announcing my candidacy for president of the United States.”

His speech started slightly past 9 p.m. Eastern time, and reportedly ran over its scheduled time. ABC, CBS and NBC ignored the speech completely, sticking to the previously scheduled programming, including reality show “Bachelor in Paradise.” Cable channels decided against airing his entire speech live, including Fox News. Fox and CNN aired the beginning of the speech, but MSNBC did not. CNN stuck with Trump for about 20 minutes before switching to a panel and a fact-checker, and Fox stuck with him for about 40 minutes before cutting away to speech reactions. Newsmax aired it in full.

Print and digital outlets across the political spectrum had all kinds of headlines and ledes. From more left-leaning sites:

The Washington Post: “Trump, who as president fomented an insurrection, says he is running again. The twice-impeached former president has been eager to declare his candidacy, hoping to get ahead of likely rivals and potential criminal charges.”

The New York Times: “Donald J. Trump, whose historically divisive presidency shook the pillars of the country’s democratic institutions, on Tuesday night declared his intention to seek the White House again in 2024, ignoring the appeals of Republicans who warn that his continued influence on the party is largely to blame for its weaker-than-expected showing in the midterm elections."

But, perhaps more notably, from more right-leaning sites:

The National Review: “No.”

The Washington Examiner: “Trump 3.0 is a changed man — he’s now a loser.”

It also appears outlets owned by conservative media bigwig Rupert Murdoch snubbed Trump:

The New York Post headline at the bottom of the front page: “Florida Man Makes Announcement — Page 26.”

The Wall Street Journal played Trump’s announcement straight up-and-down on the front page, but published several opinion pieces painting him in a negative light: “Oh, Trump Believes in Yesterday,” “Are Pro-Trump Republicans Still Gluttons for Punishment?” and “The Trump Liability for the GOP.”

“The story framing around Trump’s announcement was extraordinary from the Murdoch empire,” said Frank Sesno, an Emmy-award winning journalist, former CNN correspondent and current professor at George Washington University and Director of Strategic Initiatives in the School of Media & Public Affairs. “They have moved on, and their coverage left no doubt about that.”

Many observers have referred to Trump’s speech as lackluster and low-energy, and point out he was even less harsh on the media than he has been in the past, joking during his announcement he wouldn’t “use the term ‘fake news media’” to keep the event “elegant.” It’s unclear how Trump will decide to treat reporters moving forward, but outlets are setting the tone for how they’ll treat him, and for most of them, it’s to ignore him.

The new CEO of CNN, Chris Licht, has already come out and said the network won’t treat Trump like it did under his predecessor, Jeff Zucker, particularly in 2016 — even if it raises ratings. He said this on Kara Swisher’s podcast, “Look, it’s not just Zucker, it was everybody. We let every little thing that he did consume everything, and so you ended up talking about him for eight hours a day.” Regarding Trump’s 2024 presidential run, Licht added, “We’re going to be very clear and take everything on a case-by-case basis about what level of coverage it should be. We are not going to be a 24/7 Trump news network.”

As Sesno put it, any candidate needs media attention. The lack of it could create the notion he’s not as relevant, and embolden his challengers, depending on how outlets decide to cover other candidates who will announce bids for the White House. Trump may not get the profile he demands. Furthermore, the professor said the media loves “winners” and the media loves “inevitability.” This would explain why Trump coverage turned sour after a number of his endorsed candidates lost their midterm elections, and the spotlight shifted toward Florida Republican Gov. Ron DeSantis, who won his race by a landslide.

Sesno said the combination of news organizations ratcheting back their Trump content, Trump’s lack of social media reach without Twitter or Facebook, the underwhelming midterm election outcomes and the attention being turned to a new face spells trouble for ‘45.’

“[Trump is] so addicted to coverage. He can rail against fake news all he wants, but he loves the stuff,” Sesno said. “He will still have his loyal base, and that may be enough if the party runs a bunch of people against him and they cannibalize one another and he can come out standing tall, but I think he’s in very deep trouble.”

Another challenge for Trump that will feed harsher coverage is members of his own party making public statements against him or alluding to the idea of “moving on” from Trump — voices increasingly covered by the Journal and other outlets. From former politicians to current to high-profile donors to former officials in Trump’s cabinet, phrases like, “post-Trump Republican party,” “new generation of leaders” and “shifting electorate” are being tossed around.

Of course, these voices may still be outnumbered by his unwavering base, which includes current members of Congress who remain supportive, outlets like Newsmax and specific anchors like Sean Hannity and Tucker Carlson. Trump’s approach to his supporters — and former supporters now voicing opposition — throughout his 2024 campaign remains to be seen, but for now, he’s headed in the direction of insults.

“[It’s] not just coming from the news media, and it’s not just coming from other candidates or potential candidates,” Sesno said. “It’s coming from others deep within the party and others who are winking and nodding, not invoking his name, but saying it’s time to look forward and not look back.

“The way a lot of these news organizations are going to approach it will be to take their lead from a lot of people in the party who are saying, ‘Yeah, you’re yesterday’s news, and yesterday’s news is less newsworthy than tomorrow’s news.’”

Luckily for Trump, there are 718 days between now and Election Day 2024, so he has time to convince Republicans not to move on from him. And plenty will change in the course of two years. But for now, Trump will have to compete with DeSantis and others for airtime, and he’ll either demonize the networks who write or say anything negative, or win them back.

He’s already taken to his Truth Social social media account about coverage after his election:

“Why does anyone read the National Review? They have absolutely nothing going, it is failing fast, and my only question is, who is paying for the losses—when it loses plenty of money and serves no purpose at all.”

After Murdoch-owned companies ran stories celebrating DeSantis’ midterm wins, with the New York Post calling DeSantis “DeFuture,” Trump responded in a statement: “NewsCorp, which is Fox, the Wall Street Journal and the no longer great New York Post, is all in for Governor Ron DeSanctimonious.”

Sesno said what Americans could see is a “come to Jesus” moment for newsrooms in their coverage decisions as Trump runs his campaign and others join the ring.

“That sets up a really fascinating and very difficult question confronting every newsroom,” Sesno said. “He is a former president. He is a candidate for office. He could be president again. How do we cover that? He is twice impeached. He led a losing campaign during the midterms. He’s under investigation. How do we cover that? He’s attacked the media. He’s derided fake news and journalism. But he has a following. How do we cover that?

“The bad news for Donald Trump is that much of the world, whether you agree with this or not, their news judgment is, ‘You know what, we’re not playing into this as we did before, and frankly, you’re just not as newsworthy as you were.’ You can disagree with that, but that is the reality.”
